note: This CME is faint but visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. The source location is unknown and likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk around the time of this event.

The source is likely related to an eruption visible beyond the northwest limb as seen in SDO AIA 171 and 304 imagery starting around 2025-07-28T11:30Z. This same eruption is visible on the northwest limb as seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 imagery. Faint ejecta can be observed over the northwest limb in SDO AIA 171, 304 and GOES SUVI 284, 304 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using a few frames of SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky with only SOHO LASCO C2/C3 due to likely far-sided source and no STEREO A COR2 to triangulate. CME begins >10 HW but expands in C3 to just reach 10 HW.

The source is a far-sided prominence lifting off the NW limb, observed as field line movement and filament ejecta around 2025-07-29T16:12Z in SDO AIA 171/193/304. Far-sided source corroborated with the lack of on-disk brightening near the eruption.

cmeAnalyses.note: Preliminary plane-of-sky with SOHO LASCO C2 only, due to a downlink gap with minimal LASCO C3 imagery, no STEREO A COR2 imagery due to data gap, and partial obstruction of the leading edge in the LASCO C3 pylon and GOES CCOR-1 pylon. May be revisited with more imagery as available, but due to obstructions this analysis may also be considered complete.

note: Faint northern loop CME with a front visible to the north in running difference imagery of SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 coronagraph. No source has been found in EUV imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs. The fit can be done with a range of longitudes.

note: CME first seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-07-30T03:36Z. CME is also seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The source of this CME is most likely an eruption from on/near the W limb ~N10 beginning around 2025-07-29T22:04Z best seen in SDO AIA 304. The eruption is associated with a C3.7 flare from N09W90 that peaked at 2025-07-29T22:05Z. There is likely some southward deflection as the CME is centered about S08 once it is seen coronagraph imagery. This CME may partially overlap with CME: 2025-07-30T04:00Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best fit among SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1 as well as visible source.

note: CME first seen to the WSW in SOHO LASCO C2 only starting around 2025-07-30T04:00Z. The most likely source candidate is a small eruption and dimming centered near S05W35 starting around 2025-07-30T03:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. Another, less likely source candidate is an eruption from AR 4155 (S09W12) starting around 2025-07-30T03:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. This CME fails before leaving the FOV of SOHO LASCO C2 and may partially overlap with CME: 2025-07-30T03:36Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on visible, on-disk source location.

note: Super faint CME with a fuzzy front to the SE seen very faintly in STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery. It is possibly that the faint fuzzy front of the same CME might be seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, partially overlapping with the somewhat brighter 2025-07-30T03:36Z CME. The CME is not seen in C3 and GOES CCOR-1. A possible source could be a filament eruption near AR 14157 (S21W17) best seen (although still very faintly) in GOES SUVI 304 and STEREO A EUV 304 after 2025-07-30T02:45Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: An uncertain one-coronagraph analysis with STEREO A COR2 based on the location of the possible source (AR 4157) and on a very faint front in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph.

An extremely uncertain analysis, based on the location of the possible source (filament eruption in AR 4157) and on the fit of two very faint uncertain fuzzy fronts in C2 and COR2A coronagraphs. The speed of the CME obtained by this method ranges from 400 to 600 km/s.

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in STEREO A COR2 imagery only. The source of this event is likely far-sided as there are no source candidates on the Earth-facing disk around the time of this event.

cmeAnalyses.note: A plane-of-sky measurement was made using STEREO A COR2 imagery with a longitude of -47 degrees due to the far-sided and therefore unknown source location.

note: CME first seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-07-30T12:24Z. CME is also seen to the WSW in SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The source of this CME is most likely continued activity following CME: 2025-07-30T03:36Z from near the W limb centered about N08 starting around 2025-07-30T11:18Z in SDO AIA 304. Based on measurements, there is some deflection southward.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best fit among SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1 and on visible source location.

note: Bright light bulb shaped CME directed to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1. Its source is a slow to erupt filament which begins to lift off around 2025-07-30T14:30Z, likely from just behind the SW limb in SDO AIA 304, GOES SUVI 304, and STA EUVI 304 imagery. An opening of field lines is observed over the SW limb at this time in SDO AIA 171, 193, GOES SUVI 284 imagery as well.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit with all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). This analysis is confirmed by the location of the likely CME source - an eruption just behind the SW limb.

note: Faint, diffuse leading edge, and <10 degree HW CME observed to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2. No source for this CME is observed, but it triangulates to the far-side.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Due to the faint, diffuse nature of this leading edge, some variance in all parameters may exist as tracking the true leading edge is difficult. High confidence in the <10 degree HW.

note: Faint, narrow CME first seen to the West in STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-07-31T05:53Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a small filament eruption seen in STEREO A EUVI 195/304 around 2025-07-31T03:15Z located at approximately S15W85.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C3, GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2.

note: CME seen to the NNE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, and to the NW in STEREO A COR2. Source is an eruption from beyond the NE limb of the Earth-facing disk seen as ejecta emerging starting around 2025-07-31T08:29Z in GOES SUVI 304. Field line movement and ejecta can also be seen in GOES SUVI 284.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Leading edge becomes too diffuse to track about halfway through the STEREO A COR2 field of view.

note: Narrow CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The exact location of the source is uncertain, but it is likely associated with one of the several instances of gradually opening field lines seen along and extending beyond the SW limb in GOES SUVI 284 seen around the time of this eruption, occurring starting at about 2025-07-31T15:00Z and continuing for several hours. Additionally, there are several small eruptions from AR 14153 (S30W60), including one at or around 2025-07-31T15:15Z as seen in STEREO A EUVI 304, but the CME does not fit very well to this location.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1.

note: This CME is visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. There is a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 during this event. The source of this CME is a filament eruption and back-to-back C-class flares from Active Region 14153 (S29W68) as seen in SDO/AIA 131. Brightening is visible to the S/SE of the AR in STEREO A EUVI 304, GOES SUVI 304, and SDO/AIA 304 starting around 2025-08-01T13:45Z. Moving/opening field lines are visible to the SW in SDO/AIA 193, 171, and GOES SUVI 284 starting around 13:00Z. Based on measurement, there is significant southward deflection from the source location.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best fit among SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The early propagation of the CME in SOHO LASCO C2 is covered by a data gap.

note: CME first seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-08-01. CME is also seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C3, GOES CCOR-1, and sporadically in STEREO A COR2. The source is most likely an eruption from beyond the E limb best seen in GOES SUVI 284 as opening field lines beginning around 2025-08-01T18:00Z. This CME is only sporadically visible in COR2A and not trackable.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement based on running difference imagery from SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. This CME is sporadically visible in STEREO A COR2, but the front is not trackable in STEREO A COR2.

note: CME first seen to the NNE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting around 2025-08-01T21:36Z. CME is also seen in SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1 but is not visible in STEREO A COR2. This CME is much easier to see in running difference imagery. The source of this CME is most likely moving field lines from beyond the NE limb best seen in GOES SUVI 284 beginning as early as 2025-08-01T21:00Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement based on running difference imagery from SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1

The source of this CME is likely far-sided, indicated as a minor opening of field lines on/behind the SW limb in STEREO A EUV 195 starting at 2025-08-02T03:55Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: A very uncertain analysis based on the likely far-sided source - an opening of field lines on/behind the west limb in STEREO A EUV 195 seen after 03:55Z (indicating a longitude of >=133 deg) and on the fit with three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). As the on/behind the limb in STEREO A longitude doesn't produce a good fit, the analysis with the longitude of 124 producing a decent fit has been selected. However, a decent fit can be produced with the longitude as low as 110 degrees.

note: Faint very narrow jet-like CME to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, also seen very faintly in GOES CCOR-1 and C3 and not seen in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph. No source has been found for this jet-like CME in available EUV imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: POS analysis mainly with SOHO LASCO C2. As this CME is not seen in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph and no source has been found for it only plane-of-sky analysis is possible.

note: CME first seen to the W in STEREO A COR2 white light imagery starting at 2025-08-02T12:23Z. CME is also seen in running difference imagery in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. This is likely outflow at the back of CME: 2025-08-02T04:36Z. A possible separate source is some continuous moving field lines from beyond the W limb best seen in GOES SUVI 284 for several hours before and after the CME start time.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best fit among SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. This CME is most clear in STEREO A COR2.

note: CME first seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting around 2025-08-02T17:00Z. CME is also seen to the SW in GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2. This narrow, jet-like CME is only visible in running difference imagery, and the source is likely outflow following CME: 2025-08-02T05:36Z. There is not a separately distinguishable source.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best fit among SOHO LASCO C2, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1.

note: Narrow faint CME seen to the SW in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO coronagraphs. Its source is faint and narrow rising loop / opening of field lines seen on or, more likely, beyond the SW limb starting around 2025-08-03T04:05Z in GOES SUVI 304. It is seen also in SDO AIA 193 starting at 2025-08-03T03:57Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs, SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is likely behind the W limb.

cmeAnalyses.note: Updated measurement based on the approximate source location. Due to a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery, a triangulated measurement was not possible. The measured longitude may vary slightly as a result.

note: A very faint fan-like CME seen to the NE in GOES CCOR-1 and SOHO LASCO C2/C3 (mostly only in running difference imagery). Its front is best seen in C2 difference imagery and is fully covered by a large data gap in STEREO A. The source is not clear: it could be a couple of faint but distinct movements of field lines on/behind the NW limb seen after 2025-08-03T13Z in SDO AIA 193, but alternatively the CME might be connected to an eruption happening after 2025-08-03T11:40Z just N of AR 4165 (N12E25) and seen as minor to medium size dimming in SDO AIA 193.

cmeAnalyses.note: Updated measurement based on the approximate source location, which is observed slightly beyond the eastern limb. Due to a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery, a triangulated measurement was not available. The measured longitude may vary slightly as a result.

note: Narrow CME to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 coronagraphs, fully covered by a large data gap in STEREO A COR2. Its source is an eruption seen starting at 2025-08-03T13:27Z likely from Active Region 4154 (S13W87) nearing the SW limb. Bright ejecta can be seen in SDO AIA 304 and narrow opening field lines can be seen in SDO AIA 193. This eruption occurs near in time, but is not related to the M2.9 flare, which occurred from AR 14168 (N06E21).

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis made with one coronagraph only (SOHO LASCO) and based on the location of the likely source - eruption in Active Region 14154. No STEREO COR2A imagery is available for this time frame because of large STEREO A data gap, so no 2-coronagraph analysis is possible.

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption and C6.8 flare from former Active Region 14153 (located around S27W98 at the time of this event) starting around 2025-08-03T21:50Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. An opening of field lines is visible over the southwest limb at this time in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery as well.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

note: CME first seen to the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-08-03T23:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. This event heavily overlaps with a second front which emerged at 2025-08-04T00:00Z, but these events move as one, and were therefore treated as a single event. The source of this event is wide opening field lines seen originating from beyond the SW limb in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284 beginning at approximately 03/22:25Z. A slow rising flux rope is also visible exhibiting a strong Southern deflection in GOES SUVI 284.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1.

note: Faint CME first seen to the NE in STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-08-04T06:38Z, as well as to the NW by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a double peaked M2.0 and M1.4 from Active Region 14168 (N05E12) which peaked at 04/04:52Z and 04/05:05Z respectively. This flare is visible in SDO AIA 131, along with dimming and field line movement seen in SDO AIA 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. This CME may have been deflected towards the Northwest, as this Active Region is situation to the Northwest of a large coronal hole.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. This CME is directed into the pylon in both SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1.

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is an eruption observed slightly beyond the southwest limb in GOES SUVI 131, 171, 195, 284, 304 imagery starting around 2025-08-05T06:40Z. An opening of field lines can be observed over the southwest limb around this time in GOES SUVI 171, 195, and 284 imagery. This eruption is also observed in STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 imagery, and likely originates from former Active Region 14153 which was located near S30W130 at the time of this event.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

note: Faint CME with a complex, unevent front seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, and NE in STEREO A COR2. Source is the M4.4 flare from AR 14168 centered (N04W07) starting around 2025-08-05T15:50Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. Dimming is observed mostly to the southwest of the flare site in SDO AIA 193, GOES SUVI 284 and EUV A 195 imagery, and post-eruptive arcades begin to form in the flare location around 2025-08-05T16:50Z. There is a potential for northwestern deflection of this CME from the initial (flare) location, as there is a large coronal hole to the southeast of the Active Region. EUV wave is best seen in EUV A 195.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis made with more imagery. Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The CME seems to be deflecting northeastward from the location of the Active Region/flare/eruption location, as is consistent with the proximity of the coronal hole that is located southeastward of the location of the Active Region.
PRELIMINARY analysis using early imagery. Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

note: CME visible to the west in STEREO A COR2. Not clearly visible in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 or GOES CCOR-1. Opening field lines also visible in SDO AIA 171/193 off of the southwest limb.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on potential source location using STEREO A COR2 imagery only.

note: CME seen to the NNE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The CME is partially obscured by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in SWPC_CAT as well as source location.

note: CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. Not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2. The potential source is a C5.2 flare and eruption from AR 4168 (approximately N05W15) starting at 2025-08-06T06:04Z, best seen in GOES SUVI 195 and 284.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best fit with SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in SWPC_CAT focusing on measuring the northernmost portion of the leading edge. The CME may deflect west from the source location. This CME measurement is more approximate than usual, due to lack of visibility in STEREO A COR2 imagery.

note: Narrow, faint CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, not clearly visible in SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, or GOES CCOR-1. No clear source was found for this CME.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane of sky measurement using SOHO LASCO C2 running difference imagery in SWPC_CAT.

note: Filament eruption CME seen to the northwest in best in SOHO LASCO C2 but also in STEREO A COR2A; the relatively narrow eruption overlaps and overtakes a wider, slower CME to the northwest starting at 2025-08-06T17:12Z that does not have a corresponding DONKI entry due to its slow speed. The eruption is associated with a lifting prominence seen best in SDO AIA 171 near or just beyond the northwest limb starting around 2025-08-06T17:30Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Leading edge measurement using SOHO C2 and STEREO A COR2 of the CME which overlaps the earlier CME: 2025-08-06T17:12Z.

note: Narrow, fast CME seen to the northeast with a protruding nose relative to the slower and wider CME: 2025-08-07T00:00Z appearing directly after it; the CME may be associated with an eruption in Active Region 4169 but triangulation of the CME seems to suggest the CME rather originates from a source closer to the east limb, and indeed, moving field lines are observed shortly before the eruption around 2025-08-06T23:00Z, especially in SDO AIA 171.

cmeAnalyses.note: Leading edge measurement using SOHO and STEREO A; triangulation seems to suggest the eruption is associated with near-limb eruptive activity.

note: Jet CME seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2, C3 and STEREO A COR2A first at 2025-08-06T23:50Z likely associated with far-sided eruptive activity as evidenced by flickering field lines seen best in SDO AIA 171 near 2025-08-06T23:00Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Leading edge measurement using triangulation between SOHO and STEREO A to determine an approximate source longitude.

note: Wide CME first seen to the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-08-07T00:00Z, as well as by SEREO A COR2 in later frames. This event became too faint to be reliably tracked in SOHO LASCO C3 or GOES CCOR-1. The source of this event is field line opening seen along the NE limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 beginning at approx. 2025-08-06T23:12Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2.

note: Narrow CME first seen to the SE by STEREO A COR2, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a minor eruption seen beginning at approximately 2025-08-07T10:31Z, located at approximately S10E35. Field line opening and dimming is visible in SDO AIA 94, 171, 193 and 211.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2.

note: CME first seen to the West in SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-08-07T12:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames.
